2026-04-21 01:27:28 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['Battery in power supply module (new / replacement battery)'] hypothesis_explanation='All tests show that the positive rail collapses to ~0.012 V essentially immediately at the battery’s own internal positive connection: the drop occurs already at the “battery internal resistor,” before any subsequent PSU circuitry (LED branch, protection devices, output cabling). Continuity from the battery terminals to the + and − output cables is very low (≈0 Ω), and with the outputs completely disconnected from the rest of the system the positive output is still only ~0.012 V. The negative rail is solidly tied to the battery negative. This behavior can only be explained if the battery itself is incapable of supplying voltage when loaded by the PSU’s normal internal resistance, i.e., it is internally shorted or otherwise defective under load. The earlier replacement battery assumed to be good is therefore also faulty. The rest of the PSU circuitry has been effectively cleared by continuity and step‑by‑step voltage tracing. Replacing the (second) battery with a confirmed‑good 12 V source should restore proper 12 V at the PSU outputs, after which the downstream modules can operate normally.'
